82
00:07:43,085 --> 00:07:50,205
In all these examples, the Anchored VWAP serves as 
a dynamic support/resistance level and a reference  

83
00:07:50,205 --> 00:08:19,645
point for market psychology. 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
CPR strategy 

84
00:09:13,805 --> 00:09:19,325
The Central Pivot Range method taps 
into market sentiment and price action. 

85
00:09:19,325 --> 00:09:26,365
This particular area shows where the market might 
turn, being like a map of support and resistance. 

86
00:09:26,365 --> 00:09:33,565
This is the pivot. Above and below are two 
more lines. And all of these form a range. 

87
00:09:33,565 --> 00:09:39,805
This range tells us a lot about what might 
happen today, based on yesterday’s activity.
  

88
00:09:39,805 --> 00:09:44,365
So when you look at a chart, 
you'll see the CPR as three lines. 

89
00:09:44,365 --> 00:09:49,805
They might be close together or far apart.
This distance matters, because it  

90
00:09:49,805 --> 00:09:56,765
tells us how the market might move.
 
A wide CPR means the market might stay calm. 

91
00:09:56,765 --> 00:10:01,805
Price often bounces between the 
lines, and market is taking a rest. 

92
00:10:01,805 --> 00:10:08,765
These calm days can lead to big moves later.
 
A narrow CPR is different. It's like  

93
00:10:08,765 --> 00:10:14,365
the market is getting ready to sprint.
When the lines are close, price can break out. 

94
00:10:14,365 --> 00:10:20,845
These days often see strong trends. The 
market picks a direction and runs with it.
  

95
00:10:20,845 --> 00:10:27,005
Now, let's talk about how to read the CPR.
It's all about comparing today to yesterday. 

96
00:10:27,005 --> 00:10:32,685
If today's CPR is higher than yesterday's, 
we're looking up. The market mood is  

97
00:10:32,685 --> 00:10:38,845
positive. Buyers are in control. This 
is when you want to think about buying. 

98
00:10:38,845 --> 00:10:45,965
But if today's CPR is lower than yesterday's, 
it's time to look down. Sellers have taken charge.  

99
00:10:45,965 --> 00:10:50,925
The market mood has shifted. This 
is when you might want to sell.
  

100
00:10:50,925 --> 00:10:57,965
Here's a key point. The CPR doesn't just tell 
us about today. It hints at tomorrow too. 

101
00:10:57,965 --> 00:11:06,605
A rising CPR suggests more upside ahead.
A falling CPR warns of possible drops.
  

102
00:11:06,605 --> 00:11:12,285
Let's see how this plays out. Say you 
see the CPR moving up day after day. 

103
00:11:12,285 --> 00:11:17,805
This is a strong sign. The market is in 
an uptrend. Each new day confirms the  

104
00:11:17,805 --> 00:11:22,365
move. This is when you want 
to look for chances to buy. 

105
00:11:22,365 --> 00:11:27,885
If the CPR keeps stepping down, we're in 
a downtrend. The market is showing its  

106
00:11:27,885 --> 00:11:34,205
hand. It wants to go lower. This is when 
you search for selling opportunities.
  

107
00:11:34,205 --> 00:11:39,565
But the CPR isn't just about 
direction. It's also about strength. 

108
00:11:39,565 --> 00:11:45,245
A wide CPR is hard to break. 
Price often respects these levels. 

109
00:11:45,245 --> 00:11:52,205
They act as strong support or resistance. When 
you see a wide CPR, expect the market to pause. 

110
00:11:52,205 --> 00:11:59,085
It might bounce around inside the range.
 
A narrow CPR is weaker. Price can push  

111
00:11:59,085 --> 00:12:06,205
through it more easily. But don't ignore it.
A narrow CPR can lead to explosive moves. 

112
00:12:06,205 --> 00:12:10,205
The market often builds 
energy here before a big run.
  

113
00:12:10,845 --> 00:12:15,965
Now, let's talk strategy. The CPR 
gives you a framework for trading. 

114
00:12:15,965 --> 00:12:21,245
It tells you where to look and what to expect.
Here's how you can use it. 

115
00:12:21,245 --> 00:12:28,925
First, check the CPR at the start of each day. 
Compare it to yesterday. Is it higher or lower? 

116
00:12:28,925 --> 00:12:36,205
This sets your bias. Higher means look 
to buy. Lower means look to sell.
  

117
00:12:36,205 --> 00:12:41,885
Next, watch how price interacts with 
the CPR. Does it bounce off the lines? 

118
00:12:41,885 --> 00:12:46,765
Does it push through? This tells 
you about the day's strength. Strong  

119
00:12:46,765 --> 00:12:53,245
bounces mean the CPR is working well. 
Clean breaks suggest a trending day.
  

120
00:12:53,245 --> 00:13:01,245
Here's a key tactic. In an uptrend, buy the 
pullbacks to the CPR. The CPR acts as support. 

121
00:13:01,245 --> 00:13:07,805
Price often bounces here. It's like the market 
is taking a breath before the next push up.
  

122
00:13:07,805 --> 00:13:16,045
In a downtrend, do the opposite. Sell when price 
rallies to the CPR. The CPR becomes resistance. 

123
00:13:16,045 --> 00:13:23,245
It's where the market often turns back down.
 
Now, don't just buy or sell blindly at the CPR.  

124
00:13:23,245 --> 00:13:32,925
Wait for price to show its hand.
. The more signs you see,  

125
00:13:32,925 --> 00:13:37,085
the stronger your trade.
 
Let's talk about timing.  

126
00:13:37,085 --> 00:13:44,045
The CPR works best at certain times.
It's strongest at the market open. This  

127
00:13:44,045 --> 00:13:50,125
is when big players make their moves.
They often use the CPR as a reference. 

128
00:13:50,125 --> 00:13:57,645
As the day goes on, the CPR can lose some 
power. By afternoon, it might not hold as well. 

129
00:13:57,645 --> 00:14:03,885
Keep this in mind. Your morning trades might 
need different rules than your afternoon ones.
  

130
00:14:04,525 --> 00:14:11,485
It's all about market psychology. The 
CPR shows us where value was yesterday. 

131
00:14:11,485 --> 00:14:16,845
Traders remember these levels. And they 
often make decisions based on them. 

132
00:14:16,845 --> 00:14:24,045
Think about it. If price is above the CPR, traders 
feel bullish. They see the market as strong. 

133
00:14:24,045 --> 00:14:28,765
This can become a self-fulfilling 
prophecy. Buyers step in at support. 

134
00:14:29,885 --> 00:14:37,405
Sellers hesitate to go against the trend.
 
When price is below the CPR, the opposite happens.  

135
00:14:37,405 --> 00:14:44,525
Traders turn bearish. They look to sell rallies.
The market develops a downward bias. Again,  

136
00:14:44,525 --> 00:14:49,485
this can feed on itself.
This is why the CPR is so  

137
00:14:49,485 --> 00:14:55,965
powerful. It taps into mass psychology.
It shows us what the crowd is thinking.  

138
00:14:55,965 --> 00:15:04,925
And in trading, understanding the crowd is key.
 
Consider using the CPR with other indicators.  

139
00:15:04,925 --> 00:15:13,085
Trend lines work well. So do moving averages.
The CPR plus a trend line can be a potent combo.  

140
00:15:13,085 --> 00:15:19,805
It gives you two reasons to take a trade.
 
 
Another pro move is to use multiple timeframes.  

141
00:15:19,805 --> 00:15:27,485
The daily CPR is great, but why stop there?
Look at weekly CPRs for bigger moves. Or  

142
00:15:27,485 --> 00:15:35,565
zoom in to hourly CPRs for day trading.
Each timeframe adds a layer of insight.
  

143
00:15:35,565 --> 00:15:43,085
Now, let's talk about market conditions. The 
CPR works differently in different markets. 

144
00:15:43,085 --> 00:15:47,725
In trending markets, it's a 
great tool for riding the waves. 

145
00:15:47,725 --> 00:15:54,925
So buy dips to the CPR in uptrends.
And sell rallies to the CPR in downtrends.
  

146
00:15:54,925 --> 00:16:02,125
In ranging markets, the CPR becomes even more 
important. It often defines the range limits. 

147
00:16:02,125 --> 00:16:06,285
You can buy at the bottom of 
the CPR and sell at the top. 

148
00:16:06,285 --> 00:16:11,325
Or look for breakouts when 
price finally pushes through.
 
  

149
00:16:11,325 --> 00:16:19,245
Here's a subtle point many traders miss. The 
CPR can show hidden strength or weakness. 

150
00:16:19,245 --> 00:16:26,125
Say price is above the CPR, but struggling to 
go higher. This might be a sign of weakness. 

151
00:16:26,125 --> 00:16:34,125
The opposite is true too. Price below the CPR 
but holding steady might signal hidden strength.
  

152
00:16:34,125 --> 00:16:40,845
As you use the CPR, you'll develop a feel 
for it. You'll start to see patterns. 

153
00:16:40,845 --> 00:16:46,205
Some days, the CPR is magnetic. 
Price keeps coming back to it. 

154
00:16:46,205 --> 00:16:51,805
Other days, it's more of a springboard. 
Price touches it and moves away. 

155
00:16:51,805 --> 00:16:58,205
But in the end, the CPR is about understanding 
market structure. It shows you where the  

156
00:16:58,205 --> 00:17:02,845
market thinks value is. 
 
Also, you might want to mark  

157
00:17:02,845 --> 00:17:07,405
the Fresh Central Pivot Ranges.
This happens when price doesn't  

158
00:17:07,405 --> 00:17:12,205
touch its CPR on a given day.
This untouched CPR becomes a  

159
00:17:12,205 --> 00:17:18,685
Fresh CPR for the next few days. This is 
similar to supply and demand trading.
  

160
00:17:18,685 --> 00:17:23,805
Think of the Fresh CPR as a 
magnet. It pulls price towards it. 

161
00:17:23,805 --> 00:17:27,885
When price doesn't touch the 
CPR, it creates an imbalance,  

162
00:17:27,885 --> 00:17:34,525
like a gap. And markets don't like gaps.
They try to fill them. This is why Fresh  

163
00:17:34,525 --> 00:17:39,565
CPRs are so important. They show 
us where price might go next.
  

164
00:17:39,565 --> 00:17:43,245
On a normal day, price 
moves in and out of the CPR. 

165
00:17:44,845 --> 00:17:50,765
But sometimes, price makes a big 
move. It might go way up or way down. 

166
00:17:50,765 --> 00:17:57,725
When this happens, it can miss the CPR 
entirely. That's when we get a Fresh CPR.
  

167
00:17:57,725 --> 00:18:02,925
Now, here's the key. This Fresh 
CPR stays important for the next  

168
00:18:02,925 --> 00:18:08,925
few days. It's not just a one-day thing.
It keeps its power. That’s why you must  

169
00:18:08,925 --> 00:18:14,445
watch it closely, as it could be a 
turning point in the next few days.
  

170
00:18:14,445 --> 00:18:19,085
Say the market drops hard one day.
The next day, price stays  

171
00:18:19,085 --> 00:18:25,965
below the CPR. It never touches it.
That CPR is now fresh. It's a target for the  

172
00:18:25,965 --> 00:18:34,045
market. Prices often try to climb back to it.
 
Sometimes, price might get close to the CPR.  

173
00:18:34,045 --> 00:18:38,765
It might even have a few wicks that 
touch it. But if no full candlesticks  

174
00:18:38,765 --> 00:18:46,045
form inside the CPR, it's still fresh. 
 
And why does this matter? Well, because Fresh  

175
00:18:46,045 --> 00:18:53,085
CPRs often act as strong support or resistance.
If price is below a Fresh CPR,  

176
00:18:53,085 --> 00:18:59,405
that CPR might stop price from going up.
If price is above, the CPR might stop it from  

177
00:18:59,405 --> 00:19:07,725
going down. It's like a barrier in the market.
 
You can use Fresh CPRs in different ways. 

178
00:19:07,725 --> 00:19:14,685
Some traders wait for price to reach the Fresh 
CPR. Then they look for signs of a bounce or a  

179
00:19:14,685 --> 00:19:21,885
reversal. Others use it as a target. If price 
is far from the Fresh CPR, they might expect  

180
00:19:21,885 --> 00:19:51,645
it to move towards it.
 
Consecutive candles VSA 

181
00:20:44,765 --> 00:20:51,245
The next strategy is based on the concept of 
consecutive up or down days in the market. 

182
00:20:51,245 --> 00:20:57,005
When a market closes up or down for several 
days in a row, it often creates a specific  

183
00:20:57,005 --> 00:21:02,285
psychological environment among traders.
There's a natural tendency for people to  

184
00:21:02,285 --> 00:21:09,245
believe that a streak can't continue indefinitely. 
What goes up must come down, and vice versa. 

185
00:21:09,245 --> 00:21:16,605
That’s why many traders use consecutive up or 
down days as a basis for their trading decisions.
  

186
00:21:16,605 --> 00:21:21,325
Now, blindly trading against these 
consecutive moves can be risky. 

187
00:21:21,325 --> 00:21:26,925
It often means going against the prevailing 
trend and momentum, which can lead to  

188
00:21:26,925 --> 00:21:32,525
big losses if not done carefully.
That's where this strategy comes in. 

189
00:21:32,525 --> 00:21:39,565
Instead of simply betting against any streak of 
consecutive up or down days, we focus on those  

190
00:21:39,565 --> 00:21:46,125
that occur within a specific market context.
 
The key to this strategy is understanding  

191
00:21:46,125 --> 00:21:51,565
and respecting market structure.
As you probably know, market structure refers  

192
00:21:51,565 --> 00:21:58,365
to the overall trend of the market, typically 
defined by a series of swing highs and lows. 

193
00:21:58,365 --> 00:22:04,525
In an uptrend, you'll see higher highs 
and higher lows, while a downtrend is  

194
00:22:04,525 --> 00:22:10,605
defined by lower highs and lower lows.
By considering market structure, you can  

195
00:22:10,605 --> 00:22:17,885
filter out potentially dangerous trades, and focus 
on those with a higher probability of success.
  

196
00:22:17,885 --> 00:22:23,165
For a long entry, we're looking for 
four or more consecutive down days. 

197
00:22:23,165 --> 00:22:28,445
These are defined as days where the 
closing price is below the opening price. 

198
00:22:28,445 --> 00:22:34,605
However, we don't just enter a trade 
because we see four red candles in a row. 

199
00:22:34,605 --> 00:22:39,885
The key factor is the market structure.
We only consider this setup valid,  

200
00:22:39,885 --> 00:22:45,565
if the price hasn't breached the last 
swing low in the overall market structure.
  

201
00:22:45,565 --> 00:22:51,725
This approach essentially turns our strategy 
into a trend continuation pullback play. 

202
00:22:51,725 --> 00:22:58,125
We're looking for situations where the market 
has been in an uptrend, experiences a short-term  

203
00:22:58,125 --> 00:23:04,525
pullback (our consecutive down days), but 
doesn't break the structure of the uptrend. 

204
00:23:04,525 --> 00:23:08,685
This tells us that while there's been 
some short-term selling pressure,  

205
00:23:08,685 --> 00:23:14,125
the overall bullish trend remains intact.
 
The entry trigger comes from the next  

206
00:23:14,125 --> 00:23:21,085
bullish bar after our streak of down days.
We're looking for a bar that shows momentum,  

207
00:23:21,085 --> 00:23:25,965
a relatively large candle body 
indicating strong buying pressure. 

208
00:23:25,965 --> 00:23:31,485
Low spread candles or those with wicks 
on both ends are generally avoided,  

209
00:23:31,485 --> 00:23:38,765
as they don't show clear directional momentum.
 
Volume plays a key role in confirming this setup. 

210
00:23:38,765 --> 00:23:39,725
We want to see an  

211
00:23:39,725 --> 00:23:45,005
increase in volume on our entry bar.
In fact, the ideal scenario is to see  

212
00:23:45,005 --> 00:23:50,285
the highest volume in the past bars. 
 
This high volume tells us that there's  

213
00:23:50,285 --> 00:23:55,965
significant interest in the market at this 
level, and if it's accompanied by a price rise,  

214
00:23:55,965 --> 00:24:00,765
it implies that the buying pressure 
is overwhelming the selling pressure. 

215
00:24:00,765 --> 00:24:06,925
In Wyckoff analysis terms, this would be 
considered a "large effort, large result" day,  

216
00:24:06,925 --> 00:24:10,925
indicating strong demand.
 
For short trades,  

217
00:24:10,925 --> 00:24:17,005
the process is essentially reversed.
We look for four or more consecutive up days,  

218
00:24:17,005 --> 00:24:23,325
where each day closes above its open.
Again, we consider the market structure. 

219
00:24:23,325 --> 00:24:27,565
We only take this setup if the price 
hasn't breached the last swing high,  

220
00:24:27,565 --> 00:24:31,805
in a downtrend structure.
Our entry trigger is the  

221
00:24:31,805 --> 00:24:37,405
next bearish bar, and we want to see it 
accompanied by an increase in volume. 

222
00:24:37,405 --> 00:24:42,845
The stop loss goes just above the 
high of the bearish setup bar. 
 

223
00:24:42,845 --> 00:24:48,285
One of the strengths of this strategy is 
its versatility across different timeframes. 

224
00:24:48,285 --> 00:24:54,525
While I like to apply it to daily charts, it 
can also be effective on shorter timeframes. 

225
00:24:54,525 --> 00:25:01,005
However, I would recommend you to stick to 
higher timeframes, (4-hour and above).
 
  

226
00:25:01,005 --> 00:25:05,645
Another important consideration 
is the overall market environment. 

227
00:25:05,645 --> 00:25:09,645
This strategy tends to work 
best in trending markets. 

228
00:25:09,645 --> 00:25:15,645
In choppy markets, the consecutive up or 
down pattern may occur more frequently,  

229
00:25:15,645 --> 00:25:20,045
but be less meaningful. 
 
Now, here’s an important tip. 

230
00:25:20,045 --> 00:25:26,525
When it comes to analyzing volume, understand 
that not all volume is created equal. 

231
00:25:26,525 --> 00:25:30,765
While we're looking for an increase 
in volume on our setup bar,  

232
00:25:30,765 --> 00:25:36,765
the context of this volume increase matters.
For example, if you see a large volume spike on  

233
00:25:36,765 --> 00:25:43,645
a day with a very small price range, it might 
indicate a battle between buyers and sellers,  

234
00:25:43,645 --> 00:25:49,085
rather than a clear directional move.
This type of volume is less ideal,  

235
00:25:49,085 --> 00:25:54,765
than a volume increase followed by a 
decisive price move in our direction.
  

236
00:25:54,765 --> 00:26:01,965
Another nuance to consider is the relative size 
of the consecutive price bars. In an ideal setup,  

237
00:26:01,965 --> 00:26:08,205
you'd want to see the magnitude of the moves 
diminishing as the consecutive streak continues. 

238
00:26:08,205 --> 00:26:14,125
For example, in a downward move, the first 
few red candles might be quite large,  

239
00:26:14,125 --> 00:26:19,405
but the latter ones should be smaller.
This can indicate that selling pressure is  

240
00:26:19,405 --> 00:26:26,045
decreasing, setting up for a potential reversal.
 
As you gain experience with this strategy,  

241
00:26:26,045 --> 00:26:30,125
you might find certain patterns.
For instance, you might notice  

242
00:26:30,125 --> 00:26:37,405
that setups that occur near recent support or 
resistance levels tend to be more reliable.
  

243
00:26:37,405 --> 00:26:41,245
Moving averages can be useful 
in confirming the overall trend,  

244
00:26:41,245 --> 00:26:46,205
and identifying potential 
support and resistance levels. 

245
00:26:46,205 --> 00:26:53,085
A common approach is to use a combination 
of short-term and long-term moving averages. 

246
00:26:53,085 --> 00:26:59,165
For instance, you might use a 50-period 
and a 200-period moving average. 

247
00:26:59,165 --> 00:27:05,645
If the 50-period moving average is above 
the 200-period one, it confirms an uptrend,  

248
00:27:05,645 --> 00:27:10,445
making long setups more attractive.
Consecutive candles which end up  

249
00:27:10,445 --> 00:27:16,445
as a pullback to the moving average 
dynamic zone are a great confirmation.
  

250
00:27:16,445 --> 00:27:22,285
First, you might see a strong trend. 
The price is moving up or down steadily. 

251
00:27:22,285 --> 00:27:27,405
Then, you start to see candles moving 
back toward the moving averages. 

252
00:27:27,405 --> 00:27:33,565
These are your consecutive candles. They're 
moving against the main trend, but not too far. 

253
00:27:33,565 --> 00:27:40,365
As these candles get close to the moving 
average, they create what we call a dynamic zone. 

254
00:27:40,365 --> 00:27:46,525
This zone is where the price might bounce 
off the average, and continue the main trend. 

255
00:27:46,525 --> 00:27:50,845
It's dynamic because it moves 
as the moving averages move.
  

256
00:27:50,845 --> 00:27:56,205
When you see several candles in a row 
touch this zone without going through it,  

257
00:27:56,205 --> 00:27:59,245
that's a strong sign.
It shows the trend is  

258
00:27:59,245 --> 00:28:05,085
still strong. The price is respecting the 
average as a support or resistance level. 

259
00:28:05,085 --> 00:28:14,765
This can be a great time to enter a 
trade in the direction of the main trend.

